{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QFg2z8xHobx9yYRPYQPK6P","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t// Package handlers provides HTTP CRUD handlers for the user management API.\n2\t//\n3\t// Purpose: Registers routes for POST/GET/PUT/DELETE /users endpoints and wires them to a Store.\n4\t// Responses are JSON-encoded; 400 on malformed input, 404 on missing records.\n5\t// Tags: implementation, handlers\n6\tpackage handlers\n7\t\n8\timport (\n9\t\t\"encoding/json\"\n10\t\t\"net/http\"\n11\t\n12\t\t\"github.com/cornjacket/ai-builder/acceptance-spec/sandbox/regressions/user-service/internal/userservice/store\"\n13\t)\n14\t\n15\t// Store is the interface the handlers depend on.\n16\ttype Store interface {\n17\t\tCreate(name, email string) store.User\n18\t\tGet(id string) (store.User, bool)\n19\t\tUpdate(id, name, email string) (store.User, bool)\n20\t\tDelete(id string) bool\n21\t}\n22\t\n23\t// New registers all routes and returns the mux.\n24\tfunc New(s Store) http.Handler {\n25\t\tmux := http.NewServeMux()\n26\t\tmux.HandleFunc(\"POST /users\", handleCreate(s))\n27\t\tmux.HandleFunc(\"GET /users/{id}\", handleGet(s))\n28\t\tmux.HandleFunc(\"PUT /users/{id}\", handleUpdate(s))\n29\t\tmux.HandleFunc(\"DELETE /users/{id}\", handleDelete(s))\n30\t\treturn mux\n31\t}\n32\t\n33\ttype createRequest struct {\n34\t\tName  string `json:\"name\"`\n35\t\tEmail string `json:\"email\"`\n36\t}\n37\t\n38\ttype updateRequest struct {\n39\t\tName  string `json:\"name\"`\n40\t\tEmail string `json:\"email\"`\n41\t}\n42\t\n43\ttype userResponse struct {\n44\t\tID    string `json:\"id\"`\n45\t\tName  string `json:\"name\"`\n46\t\tEmail string `json:\"email\"`\n47\t}\n48\t\n49\tfunc handleCreate(s Store) http.HandlerFunc {\n50\t\treturn func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n51\t\t\tvar req createRequest\n52\t\t\tif err := json.NewDecoder(r.Body).Decode(&req); err != nil {\n53\t\t\t\tw.WriteHeader(http.StatusBadRequest)\n54\t\t\t\treturn\n55\t\t\t}\n56\t\t\tu := s.Create(req.Name, req.Email)\n57\t\t\tw.Header().Set(\"Content-Type\", \"application/json\")\n58\t\t\tw.WriteHeader(http.StatusCreated)\n59\t\t\tjson.NewEncoder(w).Encode(userResponse{ID: u.ID, Name: u.Name, Email: u.Email})\n60\t\t}\n61\t}\n62\t\n63\tfunc handleGet(s Store) http.HandlerFunc {\n64\t\treturn func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n65\t\t\tid := r.PathValue(\"id\")\n66\t\t\tu, ok := s.Get(id)\n67\t\t\tif !ok {\n68\t\t\t\twriteNotFound(w)\n69\t\t\t\treturn\n70\t\t\t}\n71\t\t\tw.Header().Set(\"Content-Type\", \"application/json\")\n72\t\t\tjson.NewEncoder(w).Encode(userResponse{ID: u.ID, Name: u.Name, Email: u.Email})\n73\t\t}\n74\t}\n75\t\n76\tfunc handleUpdate(s Store) http.HandlerFunc {\n77\t\treturn func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n78\t\t\tid := r.PathValue(\"id\")\n79\t\t\tvar req updateRequest\n80\t\t\tif err := json.NewDecoder(r.Body).Decode(&req); err != nil {\n81\t\t\t\tw.WriteHeader(http.StatusBadRequest)\n82\t\t\t\treturn\n83\t\t\t}\n84\t\t\tu, ok := s.Update(id, req.Name, req.Email)\n85\t\t\tif !ok {\n86\t\t\t\twriteNotFound(w)\n87\t\t\t\treturn\n88\t\t\t}\n89\t\t\tw.Header().Set(\"Content-Type\", \"application/json\")\n90\t\t\tjson.NewEncoder(w).Encode(userResponse{ID: u.ID, Name: u.Name, Email: u.Email})\n91\t\t}\n92\t}\n93\t\n94\tfunc handleDelete(s Store) http.HandlerFunc {\n95\t\treturn func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n96\t\t\tid := r.PathValue(\"id\")\n97\t\t\tif !s.Delete(id) {\n98\t\t\t\twriteNotFound(w)\n99\t\t\t\treturn\n100\t\t\t}\n101\t\t\tw.WriteHeader(http.StatusNoContent)\n102\t\t}\n103\t}\n104\t\n105\tfunc writeNotFound(w http.ResponseWriter) {\n106\t\tw.Header().Set(\"Content-Type\", \"application/json\")\n107\t\tw.WriteHeader(http.StatusNotFound)\n108\t\tw.Write([]byte(\"{}\"))\n109\t}\n110\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b90751bb-dcbc-46ad-a36d-5bcf92f90ec0","uuid":"e7387088-0a45-4cf4-85fa-8b555f876a93","timestamp":"2026-04-05T08:21:05.623Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/david/Go/src/github.com/cornjacket/ai-builder/acceptance-spec/sandbox/regressions/user-service/output/internal/userservice/handlers/handlers.go","content":"// Package handlers provides HTTP CRUD handlers for the user management API.\n//\n// Purpose: Registers routes for POST/GET/PUT/DELETE /users endpoints and wires them to a Store.\n// Responses are JSON-encoded; 400 on malformed input, 404 on missing records.\n// Tags: implementation, handlers\npackage handlers\n\nimport (\n\t\"encoding/json\"\n\t\"net/http\"\n\n\t\"github.com/cornjacket/ai-builder/acceptance-spec/sandbox/regressions/user-service/internal/userservice/store\"\n)\n\n// Store is the interface the handlers depend on.\ntype Store interface {\n\tCreate(name, email string) store.User\n\tGet(id string) (store.User, bool)\n\tUpdate(id, name, email string) (store.User, bool)\n\tDelete(id string) bool\n}\n\n// New registers all routes and returns the mux.\nfunc New(s Store) http.Handler {\n\tmux := http.NewServeMux()\n\tmux.HandleFunc(\"POST /users\", handleCreate(s))\n\tmux.HandleFunc(\"GET /users/{id}\", handleGet(s))\n\tmux.HandleFunc(\"PUT /users/{id}\", handleUpdate(s))\n\tmux.HandleFunc(\"DELETE /users/{id}\", handleDelete(s))\n\treturn mux\n}\n\ntype createRequest struct {\n\tName  string `json:\"name\"`\n\tEmail string `json:\"email\"`\n}\n\ntype updateRequest struct {\n\tName  string `json:\"name\"`\n\tEmail string `json:\"email\"`\n}\n\ntype userResponse struct {\n\tID    string `json:\"id\"`\n\tName  string `json:\"name\"`\n\tEmail string `json:\"email\"`\n}\n\nfunc handleCreate(s Store) http.HandlerFunc {\n\treturn func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n\t\tvar req createRequest\n\t\tif err := json.NewDecoder(r.Body).Decode(&req); err != nil {\n\t\t\tw.WriteHeader(http.StatusBadRequest)\n\t\t\treturn\n\t\t}\n\t\tu := s.Create(req.Name, req.Email)\n\t\tw.Header().Set(\"Content-Type\", \"application/json\")\n\t\tw.WriteHeader(http.StatusCreated)\n\t\tjson.NewEncoder(w).Encode(userResponse{ID: u.ID, Name: u.Name, Email: u.Email})\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc handleGet(s Store) http.HandlerFunc {\n\treturn func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n\t\tid := r.PathValue(\"id\")\n\t\tu, ok := s.Get(id)\n\t\tif !ok {\n\t\t\twriteNotFound(w)\n\t\t\treturn\n\t\t}\n\t\tw.Header().Set(\"Content-Type\", \"application/json\")\n\t\tjson.NewEncoder(w).Encode(userResponse{ID: u.ID, Name: u.Name, Email: u.Email})\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc handleUpdate(s Store) http.HandlerFunc {\n\treturn func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n\t\tid := r.PathValue(\"id\")\n\t\tvar req updateRequest\n\t\tif err := json.NewDecoder(r.Body).Decode(&req); err != nil {\n\t\t\tw.WriteHeader(http.StatusBadRequest)\n\t\t\treturn\n\t\t}\n\t\tu, ok := s.Update(id, req.Name, req.Email)\n\t\tif !ok {\n\t\t\twriteNotFound(w)\n\t\t\treturn\n\t\t}\n\t\tw.Header().Set(\"Content-Type\", \"application/json\")\n\t\tjson.NewEncoder(w).Encode(userResponse{ID: u.ID, Name: u.Name, Email: u.Email})\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc handleDelete(s Store) http.HandlerFunc {\n\treturn func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n\t\tid := r.PathValue(\"id\")\n\t\tif !s.Delete(id) {\n\t\t\twriteNotFound(w)\n\t\t\treturn\n\t\t}\n\t\tw.WriteHeader(http.StatusNoContent)\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc writeNotFound(w http.ResponseWriter) {\n\tw.Header().Set(\"Content-Type\", \"application/json\")\n\tw.WriteHeader(http.StatusNotFound)\n\tw.Write([]byte(\"{}\"))\n}\n","numLines":110,"startLine":1,"totalLines":110}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DEBd47ESrwjuxv1vXkMqFF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of the existing components:\n\n1. **store** package: `github.com/cornjacket/ai-builder/acceptance-spec/sandbox/regressions/user-service/internal/userservice/store`\n   - `New() *Store`\n   - `Create(name, email string) User`\n   - `Get(id string) (User, bool)`\n   - `Update(id, name, email string) (User, bool)`\n   - `Delete(id string) bool`\n\n2. **handlers** package: `github.com/cornjacket/ai-builder/acceptance-spec/sandbox/regressions/user-service/internal/userservice/handlers`\n   - `New(s Store) http.Handler` — returns a mux with all 4 routes registered\n\nFor the integration step, I need to write `main.go` that instantiates the store, passes it to the handlers constructor, and starts the HTTP server on port 8080 with the returned handler.\n\nSince this is an atomic integrate component in design mode, I'm setting `documents_written: false` and writing the wiring code directly to the output directory without a README. The main package needs to import both the store and handlers packages, then wire them together in a simple initialization sequence.\n\nFor the test command, I'll run the full test suite from the output directory using `go test ./...`\n\nNow I'm realizing the IMPLEMENTOR needs to produce both a `main.go` entry point and a `main_test.go` with an integration test that uses `httptest.NewServer` to spin up the handlers in-process and verify the endpoints work correctly. I'm defining the acceptance criteria: POST to /users should return a 201 with the created user including a generated ID, and GET /users/{id} should retrieve that user with a 200 response.\n\nContinuing through the rest of the acceptance criteria—GET with an unknown ID returns 404, PUT updates an existing user with 200, PUT on a non-existent user returns 404, DELETE removes a user with 204, and attempting to delete again returns 404. All responses except 204 should have Content-Type: application/json, and the server must listen on :8080. Since this is an INTERNAL task, I don't need to cross-reference against an acceptance-spec.md file. Now I'm ready to write out the design.\n\nThe structure will be straightforward: a `main.go` file that initializes a store, creates handlers from that store, and starts the HTTP server on port 8080. I'll also write an integration test in `main_test.go` using `httptest.NewServer` to verify the endpoints work as expected. The test command will run from the output directory.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2372,"cache_read_input_tokens":21504,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2372},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b90751bb-dcbc-46ad-a36d-5bcf92f90ec0","uuid":"a417d5a0-3eee-43de-aad8-ea696836b97a"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DEBd47ESrwjuxv1vXkMqFF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a complete picture of both components. The `handlers.New(s Store) http.Handler` already registers all four routes and returns a ready `http.Handler`. The `store.New()` returns a `*Store` that satisfies the `handlers.Store` interface directly. `main.go` is trivial wiring.\n\n**Design:**\n\n- One file: `main.go` at the output root, `package main`\n- Imports: `net/http`, the store and handlers packages\n- `main()` calls `store.New()`, passes the result to `handlers.New()`, and calls `http.ListenAndServe(\":8080\", handler)`\n- One test file: `main_test.go` at the output root, `package main`, using `httptest.NewServer(handlers.New(store.New()))` to exercise all four endpoints end-to-end without binding port 8080\n\nThe integration test covers the full CRUD lifecycle: POST → GET → PUT → GET (verify update) → DELETE → GET (verify 404). Unknown-ID paths for GET, PUT, DELETE each assert 404. This verifies all acceptance criteria without requiring the binary to actually run on a live port.\n\nNo external dependencies beyond the standard library and the two internal packages already present.\n\n<response>\n  <outcome>ARCHITECT_DESIGN_READY</outcome>\n  <handoff>Write two files at the output root. First, main.go (package main): import net/http and the store and handlers packages, call store.New() to get a *Store, pass it to handlers.New() to get an http.Handler, then call http.ListenAndServe(\":8080\", handler). Second, main_test.go (package main): use httptest.NewServer(handlers.New(store.New())) to run a full CRUD lifecycle — POST /users (assert 201, non-empty id), GET /users/{id} (assert 200, correct fields), PUT /users/{id} (assert 200, updated fields), DELETE /users/{id} (assert 204), then GET and DELETE again with the same id (assert 404 each). Also assert 404 for GET/PUT/DELETE with a random unknown id. No external dependencies beyond stdlib and the two existing internal packages.</handoff>\n  <documents_written>false</documents_written>\n  <design>\n## Design\n\n**Language:** Go (module `github.com/cornjacket/ai-builder/acceptance-spec/sandbox/regressions/user-service`)\n\n**Files to produce** (both at the output root `/Users/david/Go/src/github.com/cornjacket/ai-builder/acceptance-spec/sandbox/regressions/user-service/output`):\n\n### `main.go`\n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n    \"net/http\"\n\n    \"github.com/cornjacket/ai-builder/acceptance-spec/sandbox/regressions/user-service/internal/userservice/handlers\"\n    \"github.com/cornjacket/ai-builder/acceptance-spec/sandbox/regressions/user-service/internal/userservice/store\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    s := store.New()\n    h := handlers.New(s)\n    http.ListenAndServe(\":8080\", h)\n}\n```\n\n`*store.Store` satisfies `handlers.Store` directly — no adapter needed.\n\n### `main_test.go`\n\n`package main`, integration test using `httptest.NewServer(handlers.New(store.New()))`. Tests never bind port 8080; they hit the test server's URL. The test covers:\n\n1. POST /users → 201, response body has `id`, `name`, `email`\n2. GET /users/{id} (known) → 200, correct fields\n3. PUT /users/{id} (known) → 200, updated fields\n4. GET /users/{id} (verify update stuck) → 200\n5. DELETE /users/{id} → 204\n6. GET /users/{id} (after delete) → 404\n7. DELETE /users/{id} (after delete) → 404\n8. GET /users/nonexistent → 404\n9. PUT /users/nonexistent → 404\n\nNo external test libraries; use `encoding/json`, `net/http`, `strings`, `testing`.\n\n**Dependencies:** stdlib only + two internal packages already implemented.\n\n**Constraints:**\n- `handlers.New` already registers all routes; `main.go` must not re-register them.\n- The `*store.Store` concrete type satisfies the `handlers.Store` interface without any casting — pass it directly.\n- `http.ListenAndServe` return value can be ignored or logged; silence is fine for this service.\n  </design>\n  <acceptance_criteria>\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n1. `go build ./...` succeeds with no errors.\n2. POST /users with `{\"name\":\"Alice\",\"email\":\"alice@example.com\"}` returns HTTP 201 with a JSON body containing a non-empty `id` string, `\"name\":\"Alice\"`, and `\"email\":\"alice@example.com\"`.\n3. GET /users/{id} using the id from criterion 2 returns HTTP 200 with the same `id`, `name`, and `email`.\n4. GET /users/{id} with an id that was never created returns HTTP 404.\n5. PUT /users/{id} using the id from criterion 2 with `{\"name\":\"Bob\",\"email\":\"bob@example.com\"}` returns HTTP 200 with `\"name\":\"Bob\"` and `\"email\":\"bob@example.com\"`.\n6. PUT /users/{id} with an id that was never created returns HTTP 404.\n7. DELETE /users/{id} using the id from criterion 2 returns HTTP 204.\n8. DELETE /users/{id} using the same id a second time returns HTTP 404.\n9. GET /users/{id} using the deleted id returns HTTP 404.\n10. All non-204 responses have `Content-Type: application/json`.\n11. `go test ./...` passes with all tests green.\n  </acceptance_criteria>\n  <test_command>cd /Users/david/Go/src/github.com/cornjacket/ai-builder/acceptance-spec/sandbox/regressions/user-service/output &amp;&amp; go test ./...</test_command>\n</response>"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2372,"cache_read_input_tokens":21504,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2372},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b90751bb-dcbc-46ad-a36d-5bcf92f90ec0","uuid":"180ccbce-a001-48de-bbf2-14cf66a43bbf"}
